column1: As of 30 September 2022, will the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) rank higher than all other German parties in polling of national parliament voting intention, according to Politico?
column6: ['Non-US Politics']
as of the 30th of September they do not rank higher than all other parties
The polls are in.

There is no chance the SDC will rank higher than all other parties in Germany. Currently, the CDU has a big lead over the SDC, and with only a few days left, there is no chance that the SDC can overtake the CDU. There is no time or change of mind people will have to favor the CDC over the CDU so quickly.
Done.

Due to the party's falling in the polls over the last few months and the fact that it required a full month to ascend to the top of the polls the last time it suddenly and exponentially rose in the polls, it's extremely improbable that the SPD will rise to the top in just 2 days.

Historically, the SDC of Germany has held spots near the top of polls, and even having come close in 2021. Parliamentary elections reveal that it competes with the CDU/CSU and Greens parties. However, due to its falling in the polls most recently and especially after the Russian invasion, it would take much effort to climb to the top of all parties.
They are behind the Greens and CDU's. It is unlikely that the SPD can top all the other parties by the 30th.

It is highly unlikely that the SDC will rank higher than all other parties in Germany. Currently the CDU has a commanding lead over the SDC and the Greens have a 2% lead. With only a few days left, there is no chance that the SDC can overcome the deficit.

The SPD have not polled higher than another party as shown by Politico Poll of Polls - Germany since April 2022. Given the energy challenges, war in Ukraine and approaching winter it appears there is a low probability of SPD pilling higher. Assuming the Poll of Polls - Germany is reflective of voting intention it would require 10% of the population to switch to the SPD over the course of the next few days.
Inflation, effects of Ukraine war, and propaganda.
7 days left and they are not in the lead...
SPD made a horrific mistake in coalitioning with the Greens. They're natural partners were the CDU and they have paid horrifically for breaking from that.

With low current approval ratings for handling of domestic affairs such as COVID restrictions, energy supply, and immigration, the SPD has not found itself in a good place in terms of public polling. Moreover, the increasing support for right-wing populist movements in Germany such as Alternative For Germany, show a concerning trend for the SPD suggesting that German voters lack faith in their methods.
they won't
With 9 days to go, SPD are in 3rd place after a heavy downturn.
Seems very unlikely for looking at recent opinion polls.
Interestingly AfD looks like it's trending up slightly. Hard to see the governing party making a comeback in the short run with the social and economic trends sliding in a negative direction

Although unlikely, I'm going slightly up just to account for the unstable dynamics of the current world. The Nordstream gas pipeline, the talk in Germany of nuclear power use through the next year or so and how it relates to the Russian-Ukraine war, JCPOA still on the table, a new British PM today, new data indicating less democracy around the world, what appears to be more sensitivity to health outbreaks, economic recession fears, etc. There seems to be a lot more potential than normal.
They are criticized due to a low support od Ukraine.

While a swing of the magnitude implied by the question is not completely unheard of (see July-August of last year), it is difficult at this point to give it much weight. The aforementioned swing was catalysed by the catastrophic floods in Germany and some *very bad optics* from the CDU-CSU during and after those; importantly though, that could only have happened because the conservatives were the dominant force at the time.
Wartime in power
Kurz und bündig: “SPD…nee!”

Looking at the polls with a little more than a month to go, seems very unlikely, given two parties are ahead of them right now. Unless a big situation occurs with the SDP, probably not. However, Germany is very much affected by the war in Ukraine and by Russian gas. Something could happen in that realm to benefit or further hurt them.

The SPD is currently polling below both the CDU and Greens by 8pp and 4pp respectively, and as such there support would need to increase by quite a significant amount to be top ranked. Such an increase seems unlikely given that Germany is at risk of a recession, experiencing an energy crisis, and the Olaf Scholz is the subject of a tax scandal.
This is a test forecast.
The country is in chaos and divided against itself in too many different ways,
CDU and greens seem to be catching up, plus SPD seems to be less popular amongst Russian war
I'll pose an extreme question: what party will have leverage over the others if China and the US start fighting militaristically tomorrow?
The masses of the German populous are worried about war with Ukraine. So they will go with the party that is least likely to beat the drums of war.

In politico polls, the SPD had been the highest ranking party only for approximately 14% in the last 3 years. 3 years is a compromise between looking much further back in the past, were the SPD hasn't been on top for a long time and only the more recent history. Therefore I will take 14% as my base probability.
I think the crowd's too low on this one. SPD is only trailing the leading party by 7 points right now.

The SPD is caught between the CDU and the Greens. Tight wing parties are often favoured by a hawkish mood in foreign policy, and the SPD rising in the polls in many ways represents regression to the german mean. The Greens have recently been rising in support, undercutting the SPD, and will likely try to claim success for any left-wing achievements of the coalition government. However, this appears to be a volatile time in both German politics and European politics as a whole. Changing economic circumstances, a resolution (or non-resolution) of the Russian invasion of Ukraine, and the apparent fluidity of Green/SPD support increase uncertainty. 15 % is likely a fair assessment.
going with the crowd
While CDU is on a downfall after the last election it is likely that SPD will gain a higher visibility.

I think that while the Scholz government's foreign policy and inflation would hurt the government, if certain things make a turnaround, whether through the Russians withdrawing from Ukraine or through some (unlikely) economic masterplan, then the Social Democrats might be able to make a turnaround However if that doesn't happen, as seems to be the case, I see the Social Democratic Party of Germany losing massive ground to both the CDU and the Greens.
Recession and unhappiness with Russia
I'm revising my numbers downward for basically two reasons, both related to Russia in Ukraine:

This is not to be expected. On the contrary. The SPD has a communication problem: the chancellor. Merkel's apparent transparency and disciplined restraint in the choice of topics for her communication in partially self-responsible, regular channels (podcast), generated trust. Scholz's communication arouses irritation to the point of rejection through language, gesture and content. There is also no person in his environment who should and could pick up on this. This damages the SPD more than all of its political influences and decisions and makes it appear powerless in a three-way alliance with unloved partners.

Currently, SPD (21%) is lower than CDU/CSU (28%) but is uncertain (the popularity keeps going up and down). Since there is less time, we can move to 35% https://www.politico.eu/europe-poll-of-polls/germany
Relative popularity of the Greens creates a ceiling for the SPD, and unlikely that CDU loses more votes to AfD.

CDU won last few elections, green party has all the positive press, chancelor doesn't do much to increase popularity for his party
The SPD seems to loose popularity compared to CDU and the green party.
Greens appear to be cannibalizing SPD support at the moment
Updating to reflect recent significant divergence between SPD and CDU polling. SPD hasn’t been at such a relative disadvantage in almost a year.

The CDU has traditionally been the stronger party. Schulz will face strong opposition from the CDU on the right to do more on defense, and pressure from Greens and Die Linke to improve relations with Russia.

To answer this question, I created a logistic regression model, encoding a party's polling average, the polling average of the two other highest parties, and the amount of days ahead being looked at. For example, if at one point the CDU lead 27%-22% over the SPD, while the Greens had 15%, I would look at certain amounts of days ahead (1 week, 1 month, 3 months, etc), and record a 1 if they lead on that date, and a 0 otherwise. When I ran this on each of the major parties (as of now CDU is at 26%, SPD at 25%, Greens at 18%, AfD at 10%, FDP at 9%, and the Left at 5%), looking ahead, I got (numbers represent the probability any given party will be ahead in 158 days):
"Germany: Left party leader Hennig-Wellsow steps down"
SPD and CDU are already very close. I think this will continue. So it remains a tough call.
polls dead tied as far as i can tell

The SPD has now overtaken the CDU in the polls.
Change of mind is needed

The CDU is opposing everything the federal government is doing for the sake of opposing it. This damages it's reputation. If the SPD-led federal government imposes more sanctions on Russia and delivers more weapons to Ukraine there is a good chance that the party will rank above everyone else.

SPD is presenting attractive options to current challenges. There is danger of inflation changing the mood of the population and there is danger that implementing increased military spending will get pushback. Black swans are always possible. SPD will rank higher in September unless the shoot themselves in the foot.

Going by just the base rate, it would seem very unlikely. Between 2005-09-25 and 2022-03-31, the SPD has been on top on only 156 days. However, they have consistently been second till 2021-08-18. The answer would depend on how much of CDU's success was driven primarily by Angela Merkel, and on Scholz's performance in the months to come.
Very hard to guess, since it´s one singular day/date.
They just won the state of saarland elections and they are actually doing a decent job
SPD appears to be the leader of the coalition. The CDU is unlikely to rebuild its voter preference by September 2022.

Currently (as of 27.3), SPD sits at 25%, while the CDU lead with 26% and the Greens have 17% (all other parties historically never had the lead, so I discard them). However, the CDU has a relatively low value given its historical values, while the SPD is roughly at its mean (time horizon from 2006). From this perspective, I take my baseline probability to about 43% (CDU 52% and Greens 5%). However, the current political situation is highly volatile, as indicated by the high swings in recent polling numbers. There are several political aspects, which could play a substantial role. The Ukraine crisis could lead to prolonged crisis and struggle between the West and Russia. This could lead to "rallying around the flag", which would support SPD. On the other hand, a substantial financial crisis with the prospect of a severe energy crisis (due to a stop of gas from Russia), could substantially damage the SPD. Currently, I believe that the first scenario appears slightly more likely, which will increase the changes of the SPD. Refugees from Ukraine are currently welcomed by a wide majority of the population. However, it could be that the support will wane until September and the integration is done poorly (like in 2015, which led to substantial loses for the governing CDU, but curiously not the SPD even though it was also part of the government), which could hurt the SPD. However, the Ukraine refugees are better educated, are majority female/kids and come from a closer place than in 2015, so it is difficult to take clues from the 2015 crisis. In total, I think, the refugees have no impact as of now. Additionally, the general economic outlook appears slightly optimistic (aside from the Ukraine struggle and its potential influence), which should also help the SPD. Furthermore, there is a small risk that the influence of Olaf Scholz in the Cum-ex and Wirecard scandals is bigger than currently known, which would substantially decrease the chances for the SPD (but is highly unlikely). Additional insights from polling data might be interesting.

SPD is very lose to CDU as of today. But the tasks the government face; Ukraine war, Ukraine refugees, soaring electricity prices, soaring petroleum prices, and most likely a detoriating macroeconomy, are all issues that does not necessarily have popular solutions in public eyes. The most important will be a detoriating macroeconomy, which will combine high inflation and fewer Jobs. The respondibilty Lines with the government which will result in lower poll numbers for SPD

Historically the only post-war party they contest first place with has been the CDU/CSU. And there tends to be quite a gap to the others. So they will be there and there abouts - this question is likely to approximate to will they poll higher than the CDU.
Looking finely balanced but heading further into their elected term would typically suggest a suppression of popularity

Initial highly subjective forecast. My sense is that fallout from the Ukraine crisis combined with SPD’s historical position vis-a-vis Russia (ahem, Gerhard Schröder) is slightly more likely than not to hurt popularity. As COVID, inflation and supply chain issues continue to imperil the global economic outlook, also seems slightly more likely than not that new challenges will emerge and that the ruling party will be viewed as partly responsible—rightly or wrongly!
